									Interfaces
ðŸ‘€ InterFace is a reference type in java.- is similar to class.
ðŸ‘€except a Java interface can only contain method signatures and fields.
ðŸ‘€A class implements an interface, thereby inheriting the abstract methods of the interface.
ðŸ‘€Writing an interface is similar to writing a class but a class describes the attributes and behaviors of an object.
ðŸ‘€An interface contains behaviors that a class implements.
************************************************************************************************************************
				 					Java Interface Example 
public interface MyInterface {

    public String hello = "Hello";

    public void sayHello();
}
****************************************KEYWORD*************************************************************************
ðŸ‘€An Interface is declared using the java #interface# keyword. 
ðŸ‘€An Interface are set to private as default.
ðŸ‘€Interface can be declared using PUBLIC. this makes it visible to other package

ðŸ‘€The interface example above contains one variable and one method. 
ðŸ‘€The variable can be accessed directly from the interface, like this:
     System.out.println(MyInterface.hello);
     #interface#
     #implements#
    interface can have more than one implements. which are separated by comma.
    
  Example
    implements MyInterface, MyOtherInterface {
    if the interface are not not located in the same package. they will need to be import the interfaces. 
    
   ####Example##### 
    import com.jenkov.package1.MyInterface;
    
    

***************************************Implementing an Interface********************************************************
public class MyInterfaceImpl implements MyInterface {
public void sayHello() {
System.out.println(MyInterface.hello);
    }
}		

ðŸ‘€Notice the implements MyInterface part of the above class declaration. 
ðŸ‘€This signals to the Java compiler that
ðŸ‘€The MyInterfaceImpl class implements the MyInterface interface.

